The introductory course gives a survey of the development of Classical Studies and of the main directions in scholarhip. The examination of the texts in research of Greek and Latin authors on the basis literary and language theories is explained. Three directions on the classical scholaship are under the observation: textual criticism, research on editions and interpretation. A survey of the history of classics in Estonia is given.The course leads to the better understanding of the other subjects in Classical Studies.Objectives/eesmärkid:  The aim is to give the students a general description of the subject, to explain the directions in which Classical Philology has developed. The emphasis is on the recent fields in research and the goal is to demonstrate various approaches to the Classical texts. Students learn about other disciplines that help to understand Greek and Roma literature and culture.Learning outcomes/õpiväljund:  The students
1) have an overview about various approaches in Classics and their historical development;
2) are aquainted with the possibilities of scholarly work and career in the realm of Classics: research on language and literature, inscriptions, archeology etc. 
3) are able to associate Classics with other disciplines of Humanities.
